PiperOrigin-RevId: 525876313

Propagate errors from async checkpoint's async thread to the calller thread.

One of the current issue with TF2 async checkpoint is that errors happening in the async thread are silently ignored as they do not reach the main thread. This CL resolves this issues by propagating the async thread error to the main thread so get the caller's attention.

The implementation stores the async thread error as the internal state in the `async_checkpoint_helper` and emerges it the next time async save/write is called, or when the async save thread is joined.

Split `eager/record.py` from `eager/tape.py`.

This is done to prevent import cycles. `framework/ops.py` is a widely used file that uses the logic in `record.py`, so by separating `record.py` from `tape.py`, files which use `tape.py` without needing the `record.py` logic have a lower chance of involvement in an import cycle by not looping in a transitive dependency on `framework/ops.py`.

This change additionally increases modularity in the eager directory.

Also, delete `tape.delete_trace`, which has no usages.

Also fix several build target dependencies that were causing false dependency cycles.

Fix build breakage on iOS for gpu_plugin-related targets
//tensorflow/lite/experimental/acceleration/configuration:gpu_plugin_impl
//tensorflow/lite/core/acceleration/configuration/c:gpu_plugin
caused by commit 9765df1a06107e3dae851ce38259d25767573058.

There were two issues.  The first one is that we need to ensure that
the gpu_plugin.h header file is built as Objective-C++, not as C++; this is
important because Bazel compiles the header files to verify that they are
self-contained, and this header (conditinally) includes the metal delegate,
which references Objective-C headers, so it won't parse as C++.

The other issue is that it was missing a conditional dependency on the target
for the metal delegate.

If there is more than one non-contracting dimension, and the layout of the
transpose operand still makes sure that the non-contracting dimensions are
consecutive, it needs to be checked whether the dot shape is still the same after
folding.
Copy several end-2-end tests of folding transposes from gemm_rewrite_test and
make them unit tests, and add one test covering the additional logic.
This change is NFC for now, because we only run TransposeFolding after DotDecomposer, so there currently is always only one non-contracting dimension.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 525660488

Support GELU as an elementwise operator in the TFLite GPU delegate.

GELU activations are commonly used in Transformer architectures. The gelu op specification allows for a choice between an approximate and accurate computation.
The accurate version involves the use of erfc, which is not present in OpenGL or Vulkan.

For simplicity, the OpenCL version always uses the accurate form and OpenGL and Vulkan always use the approximate form, ignoring the value set in the op attributes.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 525645956

Enable Kernel based collectives between TPU workers.

In our current architecture, The worker service, the eager context must use the same collective manager. The first collective manager, created before CreateContext RPC call, is local. This change replaces that collective manager to an RPC collectife manager using the leader from the RPC request (which is set from remote.py). The pattern only supports a single EagerContext. I think this is almost a fundamental limitation of the EagerService design. I hope I am wrong, and please prove so.

I tried to call UpdateServerDef from the main grpc service, but it deadlocks (likely due to already holding the mutex). It is also unclear to me the relation of the worker cache in grpc service and the one in the worker session created here.
